data.content:
In xUnit, there are no setup/teardown attributes. Instead:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` | Constructor / `IDisposable` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` |

Here's your converted class:

```csharp
// Shared fixture for one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

// Test class uses constructor/Dispose for per-test setup/teardown
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key changes:
- **Per-test**: Constructor replaces `[SetUp]`; `IDisposable.Dispose()` replaces `[TearDown]`
- **Per-class**: `IClassFixture<T>` replaces `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]` — xUnit injects the fixture via the constructor and manages its lifetime
- **`[Test]` → `[Fact]`**, and assertions use xUnit's static `Assert` methods (`Assert.Equal(expected, actual)` — note expected comes first)

If you ever need to share a fixture across *multiple* test classes, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` with a `[Collection]` attribute instead.
